7/2/2022

Transcriptome reveals a clear effect of MMA on gene expression

iPSC-derived neurons from healthy individuals and MMA patients were used to conduct RNA-seq. Differential gene expression analysis was performed and it revealed that 2101 genes significantly different (Fig 8). Additionally, the change is mostly consistent between the two patient samples (Fig 9). Top 10 up- and down- regulated genes are shown in Figure 10. Finally, The Over Representation Analysis (ORA) was performed to determine whether there is an enrichment of gene expression within any particular Gene Ontology (GO) categories and identified categories are shown in Figure 11.

# Import data

counts <- read.delim("gene_counts_merged.txt", row.names="Geneid",header=TRUE)
colnames(counts) <- gsub("_RNA_GRCh38_ht2.sorted", "", colnames(counts))
colnames(counts) <- gsub("_hsneurons", "", colnames(counts))
colnames(counts) <- gsub("S113_01_", "", colnames(counts))
colnames(counts) <- gsub("S113_02_", "", colnames(counts))
colnames(counts) <- gsub("S113_03_", "", colnames(counts))
# Create DGEList object

# Define group
group <- factor(c(rep("Control", 1), rep("Patient", 2)))

# Define sample ~ group mapping
mapping <- data.frame(row.names = colnames(counts),
                      group)

# Create DGEList object
y <- DGEList(counts=counts, group=group)
# Filter low expressed genes

# Remove genes with low expression in > 50% samples
keep <- filterByExpr(y)
y <- y[keep, , keep.lib.sizes=FALSE]
## Normalize counts

# Apply TMM normalization
y <- calcNormFactors(y)
# Differential gene expression analysis

# Construct design matrix
design <- model.matrix(~ 0 + group)

colnames(design) <- levels(group)

# Estimate dispersion
y <- estimateDisp(y, design, robust=TRUE)                   

y$common.dispersion <- 0.1

# Estimate quasi-likelihood (QL) dispersions
fitGlm <- glmQLFit(y, design, robust = TRUE)

# Define contrast of interest
contr <- makeContrasts(Patient - Control, levels=design)

# Apply QL F-test for differential expression
qlf <- glmQLFTest(fitGlm, contrast=contr)

# Extract patient vs control DE results
res <- topTags(qlf, n = Inf, sort.by = "PValue")$table

# Select significant DE genes based on FDR corrected p values
sig_deg <- subset(res, FDR < 0.05 & abs(logFC) > 1)
# Volcano plot

# Annotate genes based on log2FC / adjusted p-value thresholds

res$regulation <- ""
res[which(res$logFC >= 1 & res$FDR <= 0.05),"regulation"] <- "up"
res[which(res$logFC <= -1 & res$FDR <= 0.05),"regulation"] <- "down"
res[which(abs(res$logFC) < 1 | res$FDR > 0.05),"regulation"] <- "non-significant"

table(res$regulation)
## 
##            down non-significant              up 
##            1267           15668             834
# Volcano plot
ggplot(res, aes(x = logFC, y = -log10(FDR), color = regulation)) +
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#00AFBB","#DCDCDC","#FC4E07")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12, face="bold"), 
        legend.title = element_text(size=10, face="italic")) +
  labs(x="log fold change", y="-log(adj p-value)") +
  geom_vline(xintercept=c(-1, 1), lty=2, colour = "#323232") +
  geom_hline(yintercept=-log10(0.05), lty=2, colour = "#323232" )

Figure 8. Volcano plot displaying up- and down-regulated genes in patients compared to a healthy control 

# Feature heatmap

# Extract normalized counts
lcpm <- cpm(y, log=TRUE)

# Heat map of significant DE genes
pheatmap(lcpm[rownames(sig_deg), ], 
         clustering_method = "ward.D2",
         scale = "row", cluster_rows = TRUE,
         cluster_cols = TRUE, show_rownames = FALSE,
         cutree_rows = 2, cutree_cols = 2,
         treeheight_row = 50,treeheight_col = 50,
         annotation_col = mapping,
         fontsize_row = 8, fontsize_col = 9,
         annotation_legend = TRUE,
         fontsize=8,
         main = "patient vs control \n (significant DE genes)")

Figure 9. Significantly differentiatlly expressed genes in patients versus healthy control 

# top 10 up- and down-regulated genes

# Select top 10 up regulated genes
sigUpGenes <- subset(res, regulation =="up")
sigUpGenes <- sigUpGenes[order(-sigUpGenes$logFC), ] 
sigUpGenes <- sigUpGenes[1:10,]


# Heat map of up regulated genes
up <- pheatmap(lcpm[rownames(sigUpGenes),], silent = T,
         clustering_method = "ward.D2",
         scale = "row", cluster_rows = TRUE,
         cluster_cols = TRUE, show_rownames = TRUE,
         cutree_rows = 2, cutree_cols = 2,
         treeheight_row = 50,treeheight_col = 50,
         annotation_col = mapping,
         fontsize_row = 8, fontsize_col = 9,
         annotation_legend = TRUE,
         fontsize=8,
         main = "patient vs control \n (top up regulated genes)")


# Select top 10 down regulated genes
sigDownGenes <- subset(res, regulation=="down")
sigDownGenes <- sigDownGenes[order(-sigDownGenes$logFC), ] 
sigDownGenes <- sigDownGenes[1:10,]


# Heat map of up regulated genes
down <- pheatmap(lcpm[rownames(sigDownGenes),], silent = T,
         clustering_method = "ward.D2",
         scale = "row", cluster_rows = TRUE,
         cluster_cols = TRUE, show_rownames = TRUE,
         cutree_rows = 2, cutree_cols = 2,
         treeheight_row = 50,treeheight_col = 50,
         annotation_col = mapping,
         fontsize_row = 8, fontsize_col = 9,
         annotation_legend = TRUE,
         fontsize=8,
         main = "patient vs control \n (top down regulated genes)")

plot_grid(up[[4]],down[[4]])

Figure 10. Top 10 significantly up- and down-regulated genes 

# Map gene names with gene IDs

# Load the human BioMart database
ensembl <- useMart('ensembl', dataset="hsapiens_gene_ensembl")

# Select the Ensembl and Entrez gene IDs using the gene names from the res table row names
geneAnnotation <- getBM(attributes=c("ensembl_gene_id", "external_gene_name", "entrezgene_id"), 
                    filters="external_gene_name", 
                    values=rownames(res), mart=ensembl)

# Exclude the genes with no Entrez IDs
geneAnnotation <- geneAnnotation[-which(is.na(geneAnnotation$entrezgene_id)),]
# Functional enrichment analysis

# Convert ENSEMBL IDs to Entrez IDs
upGenes   <- subset(res, regulation == "up")
downGenes   <- subset(res, regulation == "down")

# ORA analysis for GO 
upGO <- enrichGO(gene = geneAnnotation[which(geneAnnotation$external_gene_name %in% rownames(upGenes)), "entrezgene_id"], 
             ont ="ALL", 
             keyType = "ENTREZID", 
             universe = as.character(geneAnnotation$entrezgene_id),
             minGSSize = 10, 
             maxGSSize = 500,
             pvalueCutoff = 0.05, 
             OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, 
             pAdjustMethod = "BH")

upGOTerms <- data.frame(upGO@result)

downGO <- enrichGO(gene = geneAnnotation[which(geneAnnotation$external_gene_name %in% rownames(downGenes)), "entrezgene_id"], 
             ont ="ALL", 
             keyType = "ENTREZID", 
             universe = as.character(geneAnnotation$entrezgene_id),
             minGSSize = 10, 
             maxGSSize = 500,
             pvalueCutoff = 0.05, 
             OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, 
             pAdjustMethod = "BH")


downGOTerms <- data.frame(downGO@result)
# Enriched GO BP terms

# Extract up and down regulated GO terms for BP
goBP_up   <- subset(upGOTerms, ONTOLOGY == "BP")
goBP_down  <- subset(downGOTerms, ONTOLOGY == "BP")

# Keep only the most enriched terms 
for (i in 1:nrow(goBP_up))
{
  goBP_up[i, "GeneRatio"] <- round(eval(parse(text = goBP_up[i, "GeneRatio"])), 2)
}

goBP_up <- subset(goBP_up, p.adjust < 0.0001 & GeneRatio > 0.07)
goBP_up <- goBP_up[order(goBP_up$p.adjust), ] 
goBP_up$geneRegulation <- "up"

for (i in 1:nrow(goBP_down))
{
  goBP_down[i, "GeneRatio"] <- round(eval(parse(text = goBP_down[i, "GeneRatio"])), 2)
}
goBP_down <- subset(goBP_down, p.adjust < 0.0001 & GeneRatio > 0.07)
goBP_down <- goBP_down[order(goBP_down$p.adjust), ] 
goBP_down$geneRegulation <- "down"

# Combine the up and down regulated GO terms for BP
sigBPTerms <- rbind(goBP_up, goBP_down)
sigBPTerms$Description <- factor(sigBPTerms$Description, levels = sigBPTerms$Description[order(sigBPTerms$geneRegulation, -sigBPTerms$p.adjust)])

# Plot the enriched GO terms for BP
bp <- ggplot(sigBPTerms, 
       aes(x=Description, y=GeneRatio, fill=geneRegulation)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("down" = "#00AFBB", "up" = "#FC4E07")) +
  coord_flip() + theme_minimal() +
  labs(x="BP", y="") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12, face="bold"), 
        axis.text=element_text(size=8, face="bold", colour = "black"),
        axis.title=element_text(size=10,face="bold"))
